definitions: An adult male human.
example_Sentence: The man is reading a newspaper.

definitions: An adult female human.
A person who has not yet reached adulthood, whether natural (puberty), cultural (initiation), or legal (majority)
example_Sentence: The child plays in the garden.

definitions: A group of people who are closely related to one another (by blood, marriage or adoption); kin; for example, a set of parents and their children; an immediate family.
A person other than a family member, spouse or lover whose company one enjoys and towards whom one feels affection.
A structure built or serving as an abode of human beings.
A wheeled vehicle that moves independently, with at least three wheels, powered mechanically, steered by a driver and mostly for personal transportation.
example_Sentence: I drive my car to work.

definitions: Any solid substance that can be consumed by living organisms, especially by eating, in order to sustain life.

A substance (of molecular formula H₂O) found at room temperature and pressure as a clear liquid; it is present naturally as rain, and found in rivers, lakes and seas; its solid form is ice and its gaseous form is steam.
A collection of sheets of paper bound together to hinge at one edge, containing printed or written material, pictures, etc.
(collective) A group of fish or a group of marine mammals such as porpoises, dolphins, or whales.
A person who teaches, especially one employed in a school.
A person who studies or learns about a particular subject.
A task.
A legally or socially binding conceptual contract of entitlement to wealth, void of intrinsic value, payable for all debts and taxes, and regulated in supply.
example_Sentence: I need money to buy food.

definitions: The inevitable progression into the future with the passing of present and past events.
Any period of 24 hours.
Any period of seven consecutive days.
example_Sentence: I work five days a week.

definitions: A period into which a year is divided, historically based on the phases of the moon.
A solar year, the time it takes the Earth to complete one revolution of the Sun (between 365.24 and 365.26 days depending on the point of reference).
The part of the day from dawn to noon.
example_Sentence: I wake up in the morning.

definitions: The part of the day from noon or lunchtime until sunset, evening, or suppertime or 6pm.
The time of the day between dusk and night, when it gets dark.
example_Sentence: We have dinner in the evening.

definitions: The period between sunset and sunrise, when a location faces far away from the sun, thus when the sky is dark.
A dwelling.
A large settlement, bigger than a town; sometimes with a specific legal definition, depending on the place.
(chiefly British) An area of land; a district, region.
(with "the") Human collective existence; existence in general.
The part of the forelimb below the forearm or wrist in a human, and the corresponding part in many other animals.
The part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth and main sense organs.
An organ through which animals see (perceive surroundings via light).
The front part of the head of a human or other animal, featuring the eyes, nose and mouth, and the surrounding area.

A portal of entry into a building, room, or vehicle, consisting of a rigid plane movable on a hinge. Doors are frequently made of wood or metal. May have a handle to help open and close, a latch to hold the door closed and a lock that ensures the door cannot be opened without the key.
The inedible parts of a grain-producing plant.
Furniture with a top surface to accommodate a variety of uses.
example_Sentence: Put the book on the table.

definitions: An item of furniture used to sit on or in, comprising a seat, legs, back, and sometimes arm rests, for use by one person. Compare stool, couch, sofa, settee, loveseat and bench.
A piece of furniture, usually flat and soft, on which to rest or sleep.
Opportunity or scope (to do something).
A room or area for preparing food.
A room containing a shower and/or bathtub, and (typically but not necessarily) a toilet.
A device for transmitting conversations and other sounds in real time across distances, now often a small portable unit also capable of running software etc.
A person employed to perform computations; one who computes.
An electronic communication medium that allows the transmission of real-time visual images, and often sound.
The technology that allows for the transmission of sound or other signals by modulation of electromagnetic waves.
A series of sounds organized in time, employing melody, harmony, tempo etc. usually to convey a mood.
A recorded sequence of images displayed on a screen at a rate sufficiently fast to create the appearance of motion.
A playful or competitive activity.
Any activity that uses physical exertion or skills competitively under a set of rules that is not based on aesthetics.
A day on which a festival, religious event, or national celebration is traditionally observed.
The act of traveling; passage from place to place.
A large town house or mansion; a grand private residence, especially in France.
An eating establishment in which diners are served food, usually by waiters at their tables but sometimes (as in a fast food restaurant) at a counter.
An establishment that sells goods or services to the public; originally only a physical location, but now a virtual establishment as well.
A gathering of people for the purchase and sale of merchandise at a set time, often periodic.
An institution where one can place and borrow money and take care of financial affairs.
A large medical facility, usually in a building with multiple floors, where seriously ill or injured patients are given extensive medical and/or surgical treatment.

A physician; a member of the medical profession; one who is trained and licensed to heal the sick or injured. The final examination and qualification may award a doctor degree in which case the post-nominal letters are D.O., DPM, M.D., DMD, DDS, in the US or MBBS in the UK.
A wet nurse.
A civil force granted the legal authority for law enforcement and maintaining public order.
A (usually self-sustaining) chemical reaction involving the bonding of oxygen with carbon or other fuel, with the production of heat and the presence of flame or smouldering.

In scientific usage, a multicellular organism that is usually mobile, whose cells are not encased in a rigid cell wall (distinguishing it from plants and fungi) and which derives energy solely from the consumption of other organisms (distinguishing it from plants).
A mammal, Canis familiaris or Canis lupus familiaris, that has been domesticated for thousands of years, of highly variable appearance due to human breeding.
An animal of the family Felidae:
A member of the class of animals Aves in the phylum Chordata, characterized by being warm-blooded, having feathers and wings usually capable of flight, and laying eggs.
A cold-blooded vertebrate animal that lives in water, moving with the help of fins and breathing with gills.
Fast growing function based on Kruskal's tree theorem.
A colorful, conspicuous structure associated with angiosperms, frequently scented and attracting various insects, and which may or may not be used for sexual reproduction.
A star, especially when seen as the centre of any single solar system.
(by extension of Moon) Any natural satellite of a planet.
Condensed water falling from a cloud.
The frozen, crystalline state of water that falls as precipitation.
Real or perceived movement of atmospheric air usually caused by convection or differences in air pressure.
The short term state of the atmosphere at a specific time and place, including the temperature, relative humidity, cloud cover, precipitation, wind, etc.
The spectral composition of visible light
An abstract entity used to describe quantity.
A symbol in an alphabet.
The smallest unit of language that has a particular meaning and can be expressed by itself; the smallest discrete, meaningful unit of language. (contrast morpheme.)
A body of words, and set of methods of combining them (called a grammar), understood by a community and used as a form of communication.
A sentence, phrase or word which asks for information, reply or response; an interrogative.
A response or reply; something said or done in reaction to a statement or question.
A sequence of real or fictional events; or, an account of such a sequence.
New information of interest.
A representation of anything (as a person, a landscape, a building) upon canvas, paper, or other surface, by drawing, painting, printing, photography, etc.
A photograph.
A person or group of people constituting a particular side in a contract or legal action.
The anniversary of the day on which someone is born.
Something given to another voluntarily, without charge.

A facial expression comprised by flexing the muscles of both ends of one's mouth, often showing the front teeth, without vocalisation, and in humans is a common involuntary or voluntary expression of happiness, pleasure, amusement or anxiety.
An expression of mirth particular to the human species; the sound heard in laughing; laughter.
Strong affection.
The emotion of being happy; joy.
A difficulty that has to be resolved or dealt with.
Action given to provide assistance; aid.
(heading) Employment.
example_Sentence: I have a lot of work.

definitions: (physical) An area; somewhere within an area.
That which is considered to exist as a separate entity, object, quality or concept.
An individual; usually a human being.
Used as plural of person; a body of human beings considered generally or collectively; a group of two or more persons.
(heading) To do with a place or places.

The state of organisms preceding their death, characterized by biological processes such as metabolism and reproduction and distinguishing them from inanimate objects; the state of being alive and living.
The state of being free from physical or psychological disease, illness, or malfunction; wellness.
The whole duration of a being, whether animal, plant, or other kind, being alive.
(obsolete outside dialectal) An assize.
The cost required to gain possession of something.
Any nounal word or phrase which indicates a particular person, place, class, or thing.
Direction.
(chiefly British) An area of land; a district, region.
A body of words, and set of methods of combining them (called a grammar), understood by a community and used as a form of communication.
To possess, own.
(auxiliary) A syntactic marker.
To pronounce.
(ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.
To create.
To move:
To perceive the truth or factuality of; to be certain of or that.
To get into one's hands, possession or control, with or without force.
(stative) To perceive or detect with the eyes, or as if by sight.
To move from further away to nearer to.
To ponder, to go over in one's head.
To wish for or desire (something); to feel a need or desire for; to crave or demand.
(ditransitive) To move, shift, provide something abstract or concrete to someone or something or somewhere.
To utilize or employ.
To encounter or discover by accident; to happen upon.
(archaic outside of idioms) To count, reckon, or enumerate.
To request (information, or an answer to a question).
To appear; to look outwardly; to be perceived as.
(heading) To use or experience the sense of touch.
To attempt; to endeavour. Followed by infinitive.
To have a consequence or remnant.
(heading) To use one's voice.
To place something somewhere.
To lament.
To continue in (a course or mode of action); not to intermit or fall from; to uphold or maintain.
To allow to, not to prevent (+ infinitive, but usually without to).
To start, to initiate or take the first step into something.
To communicate, usually by means of speech.
(heading) to make a non-linear physical movement.
To display, to have somebody see (something).
(stative) To perceive sounds through the ear.
To act in a manner such that one has fun; to engage in activities expressly for the purpose of recreation or entertainment.
To run.
To change place or posture; to go, in any manner, from one place or position to another.
To be alive; to have life.
To accept as true, particularly without absolute certainty (i.e., as opposed to knowing)
To grasp or grip.
(ditransitive) To transport toward somebody/somewhere.
To occur or take place.
To form letters, words or symbols on a surface in order to communicate.
(of a person) To be in a position in which the upper body is upright and supported by the buttocks.
(heading) To position or be positioned physically.
To cause (something) to cease to be in one's possession or capability due to unfortunate or unknown circumstances, events or reasons.
To give money or other compensation to in exchange for goods or services.
To make contact (with) while in proximity.
To bring into a group, class, set, or total as a (new) part or member.
To proceed with (doing an activity); to prolong (an activity).
To put (something) down, to rest.
To acquire, or attempt to acquire knowledge or an ability to do something.
To become something different.
To cover, fill, or affect with lead
To grasp a concept fully and thoroughly, especially (of words, statements, art, etc.) to be aware of the meaning of and (of people) to be aware of the intent of.
To go after; to pursue; to move behind in the same path or direction.
To cease moving.
To bring into existence; (sometimes in particular:)
To communicate with one's voice, to say words out loud.
To look at and interpret letters or other information that is written.
To pay out (money).
To become larger, to increase in magnitude.
To move on the feet by alternately setting each foot (or pair or group of feet, in the case of animals with four or more feet) forward, with at least one foot on the ground at all times. Compare run.
To conquer, defeat.
To recall from one's memory; to have an image in one's memory.
(usually transitive, sometimes intransitive, stative) To have a strong affection for (someone or something).
To think about seriously.
To come or be in sight; to be in view; to become visible.
To obtain (something) in exchange for money or goods
To delay movement or action until the arrival or occurrence of; to await. (Now generally superseded by “wait for”.)
(personal) To provide a service (or, by extension, a product, especially food or drink).
To stop living; to become dead; to undergo death.
To make something (such as an object or message) go from one place to another.
To predict or believe that something will happen
To form (something) by combining materials or parts.
To prop; support; sustain; hold up; steady.
(heading) To be moved downwards.
(heading) To incise, to cut into the surface of something.
To extend, stretch, or thrust out (for example a limb or object held in the hand).
To put to death; to extinguish the life of.

To stay behind while others withdraw; to be left after others have been removed or destroyed; to be left after a number or quantity has been subtracted or cut off; to be left as not included or comprised.
To imply but stop short of saying explicitly.
(physical) To cause to rise; to lift or elevate.
To change place.
(ditransitive) To transfer goods or provide services in exchange for money.
To ask (someone) for something; to request.
To relate details of (an event or incident); to recount, describe (something).
To resolve (a contest, problem, dispute, etc.); to choose, determine, or settle
To apply a force to (an object) so that it comes toward the person or thing applying the force.
(of people)
Unfavorable; negative; not good.
Of great size, large.
Not large or big; insignificant; few in number.
Recently made, or created.
Of an object, concept, relationship, etc., having existed for a relatively long period of time.
In the early part of growth or life; born not long ago.
Having much distance from one terminating point on an object or an area to another terminating point (usually applies to horizontal dimensions; see Usage Notes below).
Having a small distance from one end or edge to another, either horizontally or vertically.
Very elevated; extending or being far above a base; tall; lofty.
Situated close to, or even below, the ground or another normal reference plane; not high or lofty.
(of an object) Having a high temperature.
(of a thing) Having a low temperature.
Having a temperature slightly higher than usual, but still pleasant; mildly hot.
Having a slightly low temperature; mildly or pleasantly cold.
Firmly or securely fixed in place; stable.
Taking a long time to move or go a short distance, or to perform an action; not quick in motion; proceeding at a low speed.
Comfortable; at ease.
(of material or fluid) Having a severe property; presenting difficulty.
(of a physical object) Having great weight.
(heading, physical) Free of dirt or impurities or protruberances.
Unclean; covered with or containing unpleasant substances such as dirt or grime.
Having a feeling arising from a consciousness of well-being or of enjoyment; enjoying good of any kind, such as comfort, peace, or tranquillity; blissful, contented, joyous.
(heading) Emotionally negative.
Displaying or feeling anger.
In need of some rest or sleep.
Affected by hunger; desiring of food; having a physical need for food.
Needing to drink.
Having an urge to vomit.
Enjoying health and vigor of body, mind, or spirit: well.
Wealthy: having a lot of money and possessions.
With no or few possessions or money, particularly in relation to contemporaries who do have them.
(social) Unconstrained.
Given to expending a lot of money; profligate, lavish.
Low and/or reduced in price.
Attractive and possessing beauty.
Displeasing to the eye; not aesthetically pleasing.
Pleasant, satisfactory.
Dreadful; causing terror, alarm and fear; awesome
Tending to excite wonder; surprising, extraordinary.
Having relevant and crucial value.
Of concern; affecting, important.
Causing boredom; unable to engage or hold the interest.
Crowded with business or activities; having a great deal going on.
With little or no sound; free of disturbing noise.
(of a sound) Of great intensity.
Not in danger; out of harm's reach.
Full of danger.
Straight, not bent.
Incorrect or untrue.
(of a statement) Conforming to the actual state of reality or fact; factually correct.
Untrue, not factual, factually incorrect.
Not closed
Sealed, made inaccessible or impassable; not open.
Devoid of content; containing nothing or nobody; vacant.
Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
Prepared for immediate action or use.
Near the end of a period of time.
At a time in advance of the usual or expected event.
Taking care; attentive to potential danger, error or harm; cautious.
Not concerned or worried (about).
Furnishing help; giving aid; useful.
Bad-mannered.
Well-mannered, civilized.
Amusing; humorous; comical.
Without humor or expression of happiness; grave in manner or disposition
Lacking in intelligence or exhibiting the quality of having been done by someone lacking in intelligence.
Capable of producing great physical force.
Lacking in force (usually strength) or ability.
Carrying more fat than usual on one's body; plump; not lean or thin.
Having little thickness or extent from one surface to its opposite.
(of a person) Having a vertical extent greater than the average. For example, somebody with a height of over 6 feet would generally be considered to be tall.
Having a small distance from one end or edge to another, either horizontally or vertically.
Having a large physical extent from side to side.
Having a small width; not wide; having opposite edges or sides that are close, especially by comparison to length or depth.
Relatively great in extent from one surface to the opposite in its smallest solid dimension.
Having little thickness or extent from one surface to its opposite.
Terminating in a point or edge, especially one that can cut easily; not obtuse or rounded.
Lacking the ability to cut easily; not sharp.
Having a texture that lacks friction. Not rough.
Not smooth; uneven.
Easily giving way under pressure.
(of material or fluid) Having a severe property; presenting difficulty.
Made up of liquid or moisture, usually (but not always) water.
Free from or lacking moisture.
Visually dazzling; luminous, lucent, clear, radiant; not dark.
Having an absolute or (more often) relative lack of light.
Having a pleasant taste, especially one relating to the basic taste sensation induced by sugar.
Having an acidic, sharp or tangy taste.
Having an acrid taste (usually from a basic substance).
Newly produced or obtained; recent.
Of an object, concept, relationship, etc., having existed for a relatively long period of time.
Able to be seen or known by everyone; open to general view, happening without concealment.
Belonging to, concerning, or accessible only to an individual person or a specific group.
From or in a nearby location.
Located outside a country or place, especially one's own.
True, genuine, not merely nominal or apparent.
Not real; false, fraudulent.
To a great extent or degree.
(manner) Accurately, competently, satisfactorily.
In a bad manner.
Rapidly; with speed; fast.
(manner) At a slow pace.
Sorrowfully.
Comfortably, without discomfort or anxiety.
(manner) With much force or effort.
Frequently, many times.
On certain occasions, or in certain circumstances, but not always.
At all times; throughout all time; since the beginning.
At no time; on no occasion; in no circumstance.
Most of the time; less than always, but more than occasionally.
In a way or manner that is real, not unreal.
(heading) To the greatest extent or degree; completely, entirely.
(focus) Likewise.
(focus) In addition; besides; as well; further; too.
Without others or anything further; exclusively.
Only, simply, merely.
(location) In, on, or at this place.
(location) In a place or location (stated, implied or otherwise indicated) at some distance from the speaker (compare here).
Interrogative adverb, used in either a direct or indirect question: at what place; to what place; what place.
(interrogative) At what time? At which time? Upon which occasion or circumstance? Used to introduce direct or indirect questions about time.
To what degree.
For what cause, reason, or purpose (interrogative adverb).
At the present time.
(temporal location) At that time.
On the current day or date.
On the day after the present day.
On the day before today.
At a time before expected; sooner than usual.
After a deadline has passed, past a designated time.
Immediately, instantly.
Another time; once more.
Without motion.
Prior to some specified time, either past, present, or future; by this time; previously.
At the same time, in the same place; in close association or proximity.
By oneself; apart from, or exclusive of, others; solo.
Sufficiently.
Very close to, not quite.
In all likelihood.
Modifies a verb, indicating a lack of certainty: it may be that...
In a way which is certain; with certainty.
(manner) without approximation; precisely.
(manner) In a special manner; specially.
Mainly or chiefly; for the most part; usually, generally, on the whole.
(modal) In act or in fact; really; in truth; positively.
At the end or conclusion; ultimately.
Happening quickly and with little or no warning; in a sudden manner.
In an immediate manner; instantly or without delay.
Used to indicate location, inclusion, or position within spatial, temporal or other limits.
Positioned at the upper surface of, touching from above.
In, near, or in the general vicinity of a particular place.
Near or next to.
Against.
Used to indicate source or provenance.
Indicating destination: In the direction of, and arriving at.
Expressing distance or motion.
In a circle around; all round; on every side of; on the outside of.
Toward the top of.
From the higher end to the lower of.
Physical positioning.
In or at a lower level than.
From one side of an opening to the other.
In the position or interval that separates (two things), or intermediate in quantity or degree. (See Usage notes below.)
At the back of; positioned with something else in front of.
Earlier than (in time).
Subsequently to; following in time; later than.
For all of a given time interval.
Outside of, beyond.
In the inner part, spatially; physically inside.
Physically over; on top of; worn on top of, said of clothing.
Lower in spatial position than.
Physically close to, in close proximity to.
Within the interior of something, closest to the center or to a specific point of reference.
On the outside of, not inside (something, such as a building).
To, toward or from the far side of (something that lies between two points of interest).
Defining a circle or closed curve containing a thing.
As a coordinating conjunction; expressing two elements to be taken together or in addition to each other.

Connects at least two alternative words, phrases, clauses, sentences, etc. each of which could make a passage true. In English, this is the "inclusive or." The "exclusive or" is formed by "either [...] or".
On the contrary, rather (as a regular adversative conjunction, introducing a word or clause in contrast or contradiction with the preceding negative clause or sentence).
In order that.
By or for the cause that; on this account that; for the reason that.
Supposing that, assuming that, in the circumstances that; used to introduce a condition or choice.
At (or as soon as) that time that; at the (or any and every) time that; if.
During the same time that.
Though, even though, in spite of or despite the fact that: introducing a clause that expresses a concession.
From the time that.
A chance for advancement, progress or profit.

The effect upon the judgment or feelings produced by any event, whether witnessed or participated in; personal and direct impressions as contrasted with description or fancies; personal acquaintance; actual enjoyment or suffering.
Connection or association; the condition of being related.
The state of being responsible, accountable, or answerable.
That which resolves uncertainty; anything that answers the question of "what a given entity is".
The act or fact of communicating anything; transmission.
The process of imparting knowledge, skill and judgment.
The body with the power to make and/or enforce laws to control a country, land area, people or organization.
The quality of being organized.
The action of competing.
The process of developing; growth, directed change.
Administration; the use of limited resources combined with forecasting, planning, leadership and execution skills to achieve predetermined specific goals.
The surroundings of, and influences on, a particular item of interest.
The organization of knowledge for practical purposes.
A long-standing group of people sharing cultural aspects such as language, dress, norms of behavior and artistic forms.
Effective management of a community or system, or especially its resources.
The arts, customs, lifestyles, background, and habits that characterize a particular society or nation.
A methodology and activities associated with running a government, an organization, or a movement.
The aggregate of past events.
A particular discipline or branch of learning, especially one dealing with measurable or systematic principles rather than intuition or natural ability.
Diligent inquiry or examination to seek or revise facts, principles, theories, applications, etc.; laborious or continued search after truth.
A planned endeavor, usually with a specific goal and accomplished in several steps or stages.
A collection of organized things; a whole composed of relationships among its members.
A series of events which produce a result (the product).
Level of excellence.

A fundamental, generic term used when referring to the measurement (count, amount) of a scalar, vector, number of items or to some other way of denominating the value of a collection or group of items.
The quality of being varied; diversity.
A group, often named or numbered, to which items are assigned based on similarity or defined criteria.
A cohesive whole built up of distinct parts.
What something does or is used for.
Matter which may be shaped or manipulated, particularly in making something.
The act of equipping, or the state of being equipped, as for a voyage or expedition.
The fact of being easy, or easily done; absence of difficulty, simplicity.
Something that one uses to achieve an objective, e.g. raw materials or personnel.
A process by which a task is completed; a way of doing something (followed by the adposition of, to or for before the purpose of the process):

The science and art of military command as applied to the overall planning and conduct of warfare.
A principle of behaviour, conduct etc. thought to be desirable or necessary, especially as formally expressed by a government or other authoritative body.
A particular method for performing a task.
A principle or example or measure used for comparison.

A necessity or prerequisite; something required or obligatory. Its adpositions are generally of in relation to who or what has given it, on in relation to whom or what it is given to, and for in relation to what is required.
Any condition, circumstance, opportunity or means, particularly favorable to success, or to any desired end.
A weakness or undesirable characteristic; a con.
An advantage; help or aid from something.
That which follows something on which it depends; that which is produced by a cause.
The power to affect, control or manipulate something or someone; the ability to change the development of fluctuating things such as conduct, thoughts or decisions.
The striking of one body against another; collision.
The act of achieving or performing; a successful performance; accomplishment
The act of performing; carrying into execution or action; execution; achievement; accomplishment; representation by action.
Movement or advancement through a series of events, or points in time; development through time.
The act of improving; advancement or growth; a bettering
A homogeneous mixture, which may be liquid, gas or solid, formed by dissolving one or more substances.
A confrontation; a dare.
The state of being difficult, or hard to do.
The achievement of one's aim or goal.
State or condition of not meeting a desirable or intended objective, opposite of success.
An error; a blunder.
An unexpected event with negative consequences occurring without the intention of the one suffering the consequences.
An event or occurrence.
An occurrence; something that happens.
A favorable opportunity; a convenient or timely chance.
A ritual, with religious or cultural significance.
The formal performance of a solemn rite, such as Christian sacrament.
A part of culture that is passed from person to person or generation to generation, possibly differing in detail from family to family, such as the way to celebrate holidays.
Frequent repetition of the same behavior; way of behavior common to many; ordinary manner; habitual practice; method of doing, living or behaving.
An action performed on a regular basis.
Human conduct relative to social norms.
The position of the body or way of carrying oneself.
A subjective belief, judgment or perspective that a person has formed about a topic, issue, person or thing.
Mental acceptance of a claim as true.
The fact of knowing about something; general understanding or familiarity with a subject, place, situation etc.
Capacity to do something well; technique, ability. Skills are usually acquired or learned, as opposed to abilities, which are often thought of as innate.
Suitableness.
A marked natural ability or skill.
The price paid for obtaining, or price received for providing, money or goods in a credit transaction, calculated as a fraction of the amount or value of what was borrowed.
Mental focus.
The act, process or ability of concentrating; the process of becoming concentrated, or the state of being concentrated.
The ability of the brain to record information or impressions with the facility of recalling them later at will.
The image-making power of the mind; the act of mentally creating or reproducing an object not previously perceived; the ability to create such images.
The ability to use imagination to produce a novel idea or product that is useful to society.
Capacity of mind, especially to understand principles, truths, facts or meanings, acquire knowledge, and apply it to practice; the ability to comprehend and learn.
(gerund) The act of one that understands or comprehends; comprehension; knowledge; discernment.
A lack of clarity or order.
(uncountable) Inquisitiveness; the tendency to ask and learn about things by asking questions, investigating, or exploring.
Something unexpected.
A person's internal state of being and involuntary physiological response to an object or a situation, based on or tied to physical state and sensory data.
Sensation, particularly through the skin.
A mental or emotional state, composure.
A set of non-physical psychological and social qualities that make a person (or thing) distinct from another.
A being involved in the action of a story.
What somebody is known for.
An attitude of consideration or high regard
Confidence in or reliance on some person or quality.
Self-assurance.
The quality of being confident, not afraid or easily intimidated, but without being incautious or inconsiderate.
A strong, uncontrollable, unpleasant emotion or feeling caused by actual or perceived danger or threat.
A strong feeling of anxiety.
(Cause of) discomfort.
